servings: 2
time required: 40 minutes
---

In a #medium pot{}, bring 5 cups water (8 cups for 4 servings) to a boil, then
reduce to a low simmer. Wash and dry produce.

Peel @sweet potato{1}(peeled if desired) if desired; cut into 1⁄2-inch pieces. Strip
@thyme{¼%oz} leaves from stems; roughly chop leaves until you have 1⁄2 tsp
(1 tsp for 4). Peel and mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}(minced).

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add
sweet potato; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring occasionally,
until just beginning to soften, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add thyme, garlic, and @butter{1%tbsp}. Cook, stirring, until fragrant,
~{30%seconds}.

Add @arborio rice{¾%cup} and stir until evenly coated, ~{15-20%seconds}.

Carefully add 1 cup simmering water to pan with rice mixture. Bring to a
simmer and cook, stirring, until liquid has mostly absorbed. Repeat with
remaining simmering water—adding 1⁄2 cup at a time and stirring until liquid
has absorbed—until rice is al dente and risotto is creamy, ~{22-25%minutes}.

> Depending on the size of your pan, you may need a little more or a little
> less water.

Reduce heat to medium low. Stir in @spinach{2.5%oz}, @cream sauce base{4%oz},
and @veggie stock concentrate{2}. Cook, stirring, until risotto has thickened
and spinach is wilted, ~{2-4%minutes}.

> If risotto seems too thick, stir in more water 1 TBSP at a time until desired
> consistency is reached.

Taste and season with salt and pepper if desired.

While risotto cooks, roughly chop @walnuts{½%oz}. Place in a #small microwave-safe bowl{};
microwave until fragrant and toasty, ~{1%minute}.

> If walnuts are not yet toasty, continue to microwave in 30-second increments
> until fragrant.

Divide risotto between plates; garnish with toasty walnuts and serve.